        In article <1992Feb28.233327.9979@qualcomm.com>,
karn@qualcom.qualcomm.com (Phil Karn) writes:

> Doing encryption wrong is worse than not doing it at all, because few
> things are as dangerous as a false sense of security.  On my own
> personal moral scale, I consider building a deliberately weak
> encryption system to be much worse than distributing a package that
> attacks it in the hope of alerting the public to the dangers.


	I think the public should be alerted, whether the cracking program is
distributed or not. I would like to at least see a description of the flaw,
rather than a nebulous "don't use this" warning. I personally was within a
hair of beginning to use this program. I am glad this news came out when it
did.

> Phil
